included.name: Diversity Science: What Is It?
included.description: In her target article, Victoria Plaut explores two differing models of diversity. She also explores the concept of "diversity science." The authors of the present commentary propose the following question: What is diversity science? They suspect that for a majority of readers, the term may suggest a topical science, in much the same way we might think of ârocket scienceâ as being a science that focuses on rockets. Certainly, terms that are already familiar within the psychology literature, such ârelationship scienceâ or âpersonality science,â have been coined in this cast. Diversity science could similarly fill a new, specialized niche. However, they would like to argue here for a more expansive definition of diversity science, one that recognizes that the general principles behind the sociocultural framework that Plaut discusses apply to just about every aspect of human behavior. In so doing, the view they propose here is that âdiversity scienceâ is, in fact, nothing less than psychological science. In other words, psychology itself is the science of diversity.
